<dl id="n12137c"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n12" href="#n12137c">N12 (VI.B.14)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n12all.htm#n12137c"> 137(c)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> posture &mdash; engram</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">While differences of opinion in respect of individual cases may be admitted, it is difficult to dispute that the habitual assumption, from infancy, of a particular <mark>posture</mark>, must be expressive of characters not merely inborn but inbred: that is, of <mark>engrams</mark>. <small> F.G. Crookshank, <a name="MIOM" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#MIOM"><cite title="source">The Mongol in Our Midst</cite></a> (1924) 39 [in the subsection Posture (a topic that has &ldquo;escaped the attention of most anthropologists&rdquo;)]</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
